What are some good design references for 3D UIs?
props.summary: Some good design references for 3D UIs include Apple's Human Interface Guidelines, Google's Material Design, Unity's Best Practices, and Valve's VR UI Guidelines.

props.text: Here are some good design references for 3D UIs:

• [[Apple Human Interface]] Guidelines - Apple has extensive guidelines for designing intuitive and usable 3D interfaces, especially for iOS and macOS. They cover things like use of lighting, shadows, materials, textures, animation, and interaction.

• [[Google Material Design]] - Google's Material Design principles also apply to 3D interfaces, with a focus on simplicity, responsiveness, and meaningfulness. Things like flat design, elevation, animation, and motion are covered.

• [[Unity UI Best Practices]] - Unity has a set of recommendations for designing 3D UIs in their engine, covering layouts, text, buttons, sliders, menus, etc. They provide example assets and templates.

• Valve's VR UI Guidelines - Valve published a set of guidelines specifically for designing VR user interfaces, based on their experience developing VR games like The Lab and Half-Life: Alyx. They cover text legibility, widget sizing, interaction techniques, and more.

• 3D UI Patterns - Sites like UI-Patterns.com and UI-Patterns.com provide examples of common 3D UI elements and patterns you can draw inspiration from, like menus, buttons, sliders, progress bars, tooltips, etc.
• Example 3D Apps - Looking at how other apps have designed their 3D UIs can provide a lot of inspiration. Games, VR apps, and 3D
Here are some novel challenges to designing 3D UIs compared to 2D UIs:

props.name: What are some novel challenges to designing 3D UIs that don't exist in 2D?
props.summary: Some challenges that designers face when designing 3D UIs are depth perception, navigation, occlusion, and cognitive load. These challenges need to be taken into account when designing the UI, and designers need to be aware of how these challenges might affect users.

props.text: 1. Depth perception - Users need to perceive depth and distances in 3D space, which can be challenging. This requires special design considerations to aid depth perception.

2. Navigation - Navigating in 3D space is more complex than 2D. Users need to be able to move in 3 axes (forward/back, left/right, up/down) instead of just 2 axes. This requires new navigation metaphors and controls.
3. Occlusion - Objects can occlude or hide other objects in 3D, which does not happen in typical 2D interfaces. The UI needs to account for what is visible to the user at any given time.

4. 3D object manipulation - Users need ways to select, manipulate and interact with 3D objects, which is more complex than interacting with 2D elements. This requires new interaction techniques and controls.

5. Stereoscopic viewing - For true 3D, stereoscopic displays are often used which present a different image to each eye. This requires special design for vergence-accommodation conflict, fatigue, and other visual issues.

6. Cognitive load - In general, 3D UIs tend to place a higher cognitive load on users due to the increased complexity of 3D perception and interaction. The UI design needs to account for and mitigate this increased load.

props.name: Please outline a user testing framework for refining our 3D UI design.
props.summary: This user testing framework can help you improve your 3D UI design by identifying areas of difficulty and confusion for your target audience.

props.text: Here is a suggested [[user testing]] framework for refining your [[3D UI design]]:
1. Recruit a diverse set of test users. You'll want a mix of ages, genders, experience levels with 3D interfaces, and roles within your target audience. Aim for around 8-10 test users total.

2. Conduct a think aloud [[usability]] test. Have the users perform representative tasks while verbally describing what they are doing, thinking, and feeling. This will provide valuable insights into any usability issues or [[points of confusion]].
3. Focus on key metrics. Track metrics like [[task completion rate]], time on task, number of errors, and [[user satisfaction]]. Look for areas where performance is poor or satisfaction is low.

4. Observe users' interactions closely. Pay attention to things like how they manipulate 3D objects, navigate the interface, and interpret visual elements. Note any difficulties or frustrations they encounter.
5. Ask [[open-ended questions]]. During and after the test, ask users to describe their experience in their own words. Probe for details about what was difficult, confusing, or unexpected.
6. Gather specific improvement suggestions. In addition to general feedback, ask users how they think the interface could be improved. Capture their recommended changes and redesign suggestions.
